International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this posting:
[1] National
[2] São Paulo

******
[1] National
Date: Wed 10 Jan 2018 09:43 BRST
Source: Spanish People [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://spanish.people.com.cn/n3/2018/0110/c31617-9313672.html


The Brazil Ministry of Health today [10 Jan 2017] announced a "fractionated" vaccination campaign in the states of São Paulo, Río de Janeiro, and Bahía, with the goal of immunizing 19.7 million people against yellow fever, due to the increase in cases since last year [2017].

In an announcement, the agency stated that in order to have an effective campaign, the states will adopt the fractionated dose method, that is to say, a dose of the yellow fever vaccine that would normally be applied to just one person will now reach 4. According to the Ministry, a single dose could cover 5 people, but the government will work with a "safety margin". [The fractionated dose strategy used in the vaccination campaign in DR Congo was 1/5 of the normal dose, with a single dose covering 5 people. Apparently, the Brazil strategy is to apply 1/4 the usual dose. - Mod.TY]

The fractionated dose will not be given to all; for children 9 months-2 years, people with specific clinical conditions such as patients with HIV AIDS, pregnant, and international travelers will continue to receive the [full] standard dose.

A total of 15 million Brazilians will receive the fractionated dose and another 4.7 million the standard dose in 75 municipalities in the states being considered.

The division of the usual dose has been studied by he Ministry of Health for some time, although it began to be considered for implementation in March of [2017], according to a statement issued by the head of the agency, Ricardo Barros, who was cited in the communication. "The results of people who received the fractioned dose was followed for 8 years and their immunity is the same as those receiving the standard dose," he explained.

This will be the 1st time that the vaccine has been divided in Brazil, a method that was used in Africa in 2016.

This Tuesday morning [9 Jan 2018], the São Paulo Secretariat of Public Health stated that the number of fatal cases of the disease increased to 13, 3 of whom were in the São Paulo metropolitan region.

This is the 1st time since 1942 that cases of urban yellow fever have been registered. [These were cases of spill-over from the sylvan (forest) transmission cycle, not the urban _Aedes aegypti_ transmission cycle, but are the 1st to occur in the urban, metropolitan area. - Mod.TY]

The vaccines for the campaign will be produced and provided by Bio-Manguinhos, a state laboratory of Fiocruz, the institution that did the tests on the fractionated vaccine.

"We do not know what is going to happen with the yellow fever area this year [2018], but as a precaution we are regulating our (existing) stock, keeping some vaccine in stock, for future needs," said Barros.

The fractionation strategy is a preventive measure recommended by the World Health Organization in special cases. This measure is advised when there is an increase in the epizootic (an epidemic affecting animals) and cases of intensive sylvan [forest] yellow fever, with risk of spill-over of the disease in populated cities and that have not had vaccination recommended for some time. According to the Ministry of Health, studies done by Fiocruz assure that a person vaccinated with a fractioned dose will have at least 8 years of immunity.

Yellow fever is an infectious, acute febrile disease caused by a virus that can lead to an individual's death in the lapse of a week if not treated rapidly. The most common symptoms of the disease are high fever, chills, fatigue, headache, muscle pain, nausea, and vomiting that can last on average 3 days.

The virus is transmitted by the bite of a vector mosquito and there is not direct transmission between an infected person and another.

Currently, there is no existing specific treatment against the virus [infection], so that treatment is symptomatic with different methods seeking to remediate as much as possible any organ failure, awaiting the recuperation of the patient.

