******
[2] São Paulo
Date: Thu 11 Jan 2018
Source: The Rio Times [edited]
http://riotimesonline.com/brazil-news/rio-politics/yellow-fever-vaccination-campaign-to-start-in-sao-paulo/


After the confirmation of at least 12 deaths in 2017 from yellow fever in the São Paulo metropolitan area, health officials have announced a massive vaccination campaign against yellow fever [starting] in February [2018]. Authorities say that the vaccine given during the campaign, however, will be 'fractionated', or divided into 4 doses.

"There is no difference in efficacy between fractional and integral vaccines. What we are discussing is the time protection lasts with a level of sufficient antibodies for a number of years," noted David Uip, São Paulo state's Health Secretary, trying to dispel rumors that there may not be enough vaccines to go around.

The fractionated dose was defined by a Ministry of Health directive, and has proven efficacy for 8 years, while the full dose lasts a lifetime. According to officials, however, children between 9 months and 2 years, pregnant women in risk areas, those with renal and diabetes problems, and those travelling to countries where the vaccine is required, will be given the full dose.

"The expectation is that, with the fractionated dose about 4.5 million people will be vaccinated and another 1.5 million will be given the full dose," explained Rejane de Paula, director of the Center for Epidemiological Surveillance for São Paulo state during a press conference earlier this week.

The campaign will run from [3-24 Feb 2018] and target 53 cities including the capital, São Paulo city. Meanwhile authorities urge residents who haven't been vaccinated to avoid parks and wooded areas where the mosquito carrying the yellow fever virus may be found.

Last October [2017] 13 parks in the city were closed as a precaution after monkeys infected with the yellow fever virus were found dead in the area. In late December [2017] another 10 urban parks in the south and west of São Paulo city were closed indefinitely, "as a measure to prevent the spread of yellow fever", according to officials.

[Byline: Lise Alves]

